	<!-- custom: rename "Ivory" to "Elephants". Here the main reasons for this change: 
	- 1) you need elephants to build war elephants, not ivory, even if you were to somehow find ivory somewhere, it would/could not magically turn into a war elephant, so using the animal instead.
	- 2) ivory doesn't grow on the groud i think if i am not mistaken, but is derived from elephants, independent of whether they are alive or dead.
	- 3) One could also maybe imagine that elephants the animal itself makes people happy, and not necessarily their ivory.
	note: Since they are part of the animals that are countable in english rather than uncountable (see code comment below about cattle) and seeing that civ4 doesn't seem to bother with singulars too much about animals at least. I also prefer this version, anyways. -->
	<TEXT>
		<Tag>TXT_KEY_BONUS_ELEPHANTS</Tag>
		<English>Elephants</English>
	</TEXT>



	<!-- custom: similarly to what was done with the elephants, "Cattle" seems a better
	fit to me than "Cow".
	Be careful, according to, for example: https://forum.wordreference.com/threads/sheep-countable-uncountable.2057034/post-13154720 , some animals are countable (5 cats for example) in English while others are best fit at singular (5 sheep for example)
	There are less gains in changing what is already working. But specifically for cattle however rather than cows as it applies to all sexes of the cows, while still being specific and not generic if i'm not mistaken: https://www.idausa.org/campaign/guardian/latest-news/difference-cows-cattle-meaning/#:~:text=The%20difference%20between%20cows%20and,strictly%20to%20mature%20female%20bovines.
	https://context.reverso.net/translation/english-french/cows
	Also the audio announcer says in https://civilization.fandom.com/wiki/Animal_Husbandry_(Civ4): "Blessed shall be the fruit of thy cattle, the increase of thy kine, and the flocks of thy sheep." - The Bible, Deuteronomy 28:4
	So i think it's very immersive and nice to use cattle here too on top of being more accurate it seems. -->
